<HL>
   Southwestern Bell,
   Ameritech Say Profits
   Edged Up in Quarter
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
04/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   SBC AIT
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Two regional Bell operating companies reported modest
first-quarter earnings growth. Southwestern Bell Corp. said
net income increased 3.8%, reflecting strong growth in access
lines and cellular telephone customers. Ameritech Corp. said
its earnings rose less than 1% because of one-time expenses
related to work force reductions.
   St. Louis-based Southwestern Bell posted net income of
$247.8 million, or 82 cents a share, up from $238.8 million,
or 79 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue
increased 3.5% to $2.13 billion from $2.06 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Edward E. Whitacre Jr., Southwestern Bell chairman, said
cellular customers increased by 59,000, or 15.4%, and access
lines increased by 114,600, or 1%, during the first quarter.
Operating expenses rose 4.1% to $1.67 billion. Positive rate
adjustments also contributed to higher earnings, Mr. Whitacre
said.
   Ameritech's net income grew 0.9% to $303.5 million, or
$1.13 a share, from $300.8 million, or $1.12 a share, in the
year-ago first quarter. Revenue rose 4.7% to $2.62 billion
from $2.50 billion. Expenses increased 5.6% to $2.18 billion
from $2.06 billion.
   William L. Weiss, Ameritech chairman, said results were
affected by one-time expenses of $54 million related to work
force reductions totalling 1,265 at Illinois Bell and
Michigan Bell. Excluding one-time charges, expenses rose
3.2%. Customer access lines increased by 142,000, or 0.9%,
and cellular customers increased by 15,000, or 6.2% during
the first quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900418-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900418-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- TRW Inc.:
   First-Period Net Fell 17%
   Higher Interest Costs Cited
</HL>
<DATE>
04/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TRW
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TRW Inc. reported a 17% decline in first-quarter profit
mainly because of higher interest expense.
   The automotive parts, defense and space contracting and
information services concern earned $57 million, or 92 cents
a share, down from $69 million, or $1.12 a share, a year
earlier. The Cleveland-based company reports share earnings
on a fully diluted basis.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales rose 12% to $1.99 billion from $1.79 billion.
   Operating profit from the three major business groups rose
to $159 million, from $150 million a year earlier, TRW said,
but interest expense climbed to $52 million, from $29 million
in the 1989 quarter. Borrowing for two major acquisitions in
1989, combined with soaring interest rates in Brazil to raise
interest costs.
   Auto and truck-parts operations showed a 7% rise in
operating profit on a 15% sales gain, TRW said. Higher sales
of occupant-restraint systems, in addition to a strong
European market, more than offset the soft North American
market and problems in Brazil.
   Operating profit from space and defense contracting rose
12% on a 4% sales rise. And the information systems and
services business had a 40% operating profit rise.
</TEXT>
