<HL>
   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
04/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP TOYOY J.ACI C SDO FNM
</CO>
<IN>
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   San Diego Gas &amp; Electric Co. -- $100 million of first
mortgage bonds, due April 15, 2020, was won in competitive
bidding by a Merrill Lynch Capital Markets group and was
priced with a coupon of 9 5/8% at 98.45 to yield 9.785%. The
bonds, which are non-callable for 10 years, were priced at a
spread of 1.05 percentage points above the Treasury's 30-year
bellwether bond. The winning bid resulted in a net interest
cost to the company of 9.833%. The issue is rated double-A-3
by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and single-A-plus by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Santa Clara County Traffic Authority, Calif. -- $274.9
million of sales tax revenue bonds, (limited tax bonds), 1990
Series, due April 1, 1992-1995, were tentatively priced by a
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. group to yield from 6.20% in 1992 to
6.50% in 1995. There are no term bonds. The bonds are insured
and rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Louisiana -- $263 million of gasoline and fuels tax
revenue bonds, 1990 Series A, due Nov. 15, 1993-2000, and
2004, with capital appreciation bonds due Nov. 15, 2001 and
2002, were priced by a Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. group. The bonds
are priced to yield from 6.65% in 1993 to 7.45% in 2004.
Current interest serial bonds are priced to yield from 6.65%
in 1993 to 7.30% in 2000. There are $63.5 million of 7 1/4%
term bonds priced at 98.24 to yield 7.45% in 2004. Capital
appreciation bonds are priced to yield to maturity to 7.25%
in 2001 and 2002. The bonds are rated single-A by Moody's and
single-A-minus by S&amp;P, excluding bonds due in 1996-1998, 2001
and 2002, which are insured and rated triple-A by both firms.
   Tennessee Housing Development Agency -- $75 million of
home-ownership program revenue bonds, Issue P due July ,
1998-1999 and 2017, with capital appreciation bonds due Jan.
1 and July 1, 2000-2010, and Series Q, due July 1, 2022, were
tentatively priced by a Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
group to yield from 6.90% for Series P bonds due in 1998 to
7.88% for Series Q bonds due in 2022. Current interest serial
bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.90% in 1998 to 7.00%
in 1999. There are $23 million of term bonds priced at par to
yield 7 5/8% in 2017. Capital appreciation bonds are priced
to yield to maturity from 7.10% in 2000 to 7.50% in
2008-2010. Series Q consists of $35 million of term bonds
priced at par to yield 7 7/8% in 2022. Interest on Series Q
bonds will be treated as a preference item in calculating the
federal alternative minimum tax that may be imposed on
certain investors. A single-A rating is expected from
Moody's, and a single-A-plus rating is expected from S&amp;P,
according to an official with the lead underwriter.
                                                                                                       

                      MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
real estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in 15 classes by PaineWebber Inc. The issue, Fannie
Mae's Series 1990-53, is backed by Fannie Mae 9% securities
with a weighted average remaining term to maturity of 29.4
years. Details on yields weren't immediately available.
                                                                                                       

                         ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Chrysler Financial Corp. -- $609.3 million of securities
backed by automobile loans with a coupon rate of 9 1/4% at 99
35/64 to yield 9.501% through First Boston Corp. The issue is
being made through Asset-Backed Securities Corp. 7, a company
formed by First Boston for issuing asset securities. The
issue was priced at a yield spread of 0.80 percentage point
above the Treasury two-year note. The securities have an
estimated average life of 1.5 years. The scheduled maturity
date is April 15, 1995. The securities are expected to carry
triple-A ratings from Moody's and S&amp;P based on the quality of
the underlying loans and a letter of credit covering 9% of
the issue from Credit Suisse. Principal and interest payments
will be made monthly.
                                                                                                       

                        EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Deutsche Girozentrale (West Germany) -- 125 million Swiss
francs ($83.9 million) of 7 1/2% public bonds due May 21,
1995, priced at 101 1/2 via Swiss Bank Corp.
   Toyota Motor Credit Corp. (U.S.) -- 100 million Swiss
francs of 8% privately placed notes due May 8, 1993, priced
at 101.13 via Swiss Bank.
   Ascii Corp. (Japan) -- 50 million marks ($29.8 million) of
9 1/8% private placement bonds due April 20, 1994, priced at
101 1/2 to yield 8.67%, via Industriebank von Japan
(Deutschland) AG. Guarenteed by Industrial Bank of Japan.
</TEXT>
