<HL>
   United Telecom to Acquire GTE Stake
   Of 19.9% in US Sprint for $500 Million
   ----
   By Johnnie L. Roberts
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   UT GTE WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   United Telecommunications Inc. said it plans to acquire
GTE Corp.'s remaining 19.9% stake in US Sprint Communications
Co. for $500 million.
   William T. Esrey, United Telecom's chairman, president and
chief executive officer, told shareholders that the Kansas
City, Mo., company will pay book value for the interest, in a
transaction expected to be completed by early July.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The purchase was expected, under terms of a 1988 agreement
in which United Telecom and GTE ended their 50-50 partnership
in the long-distance telephone service venture, and United
Telecom boosted its holding to 79.1%. US Sprint is the
third-largest long-distance telephone service, with $1.2
billion of revenue in the first quarter, up 24%.
   Separately, United and GTE, based in Stamford, Conn.,
posted first-quarter profit gains of 41% and 8%,
respectively. United's revenue grew by 24% and GTE's 9%. Both
gains were in line with the expectations of financial
analysts.
   Yesterday, in composite trading on the New York Stock
Exchange, United Telecom closed at $39.875 a share, down 25
cents a share. GTE closed at $66, off 37.5 cents a share.
   At United's annual meeting, as expected, shareholders
approved a measure to rename the company Sprint Corp. after
purchase of the 19.9% stake from GTE. And Mr. Esrey, 50 years
old, assumed the title of chairman, succeeding Paul H.
Henson, 64, who retired but who will continue as a director.
   In an interview, Mr. Esrey said United plans to finance
the transaction with loans and that the acquisition won't
dilute earnings. "We always said we would exercise the
{purchase} option when financial results of Sprint justified
the cost of the buyout," he said.
   Analysts concurred in his optimism about the long-term
outlook. Sprint's "momentum is very strong," said Jack
Grubman of Paine Webber.
   For the first quarter, United had net income of $106.9
million, or 51 cents a share, up from $75.6 million, or 36
cents a share, the year earlier. Revenue jumped to $2.02
billion from $1.77 billion.
   At Sprint, operating profit climbed sharply -- to $85
million from $31 million as revenue jumped 24% to $1.2
billion. Even so, the revenue growth didn't meet internal
expectations largely because, analysts said, one or two
contracts weren't booked in the period by Sprint's Telenet
communications network operation.
   United's local telephone company operations posted
operating earnings of $169 million, up $12 million, or 7.6%,
from a year ago. Revenue rose more than 3% to $662 million
from $641 million the year before.
   At GTE, net totaled $355.2 million, or $1.05 a share, up
from $329.2 million, or 97 cents a share, the year before.
Revenue increased to $4.5 billion from $4.12 billion.
   Despite a $101 million rate reduction, GTE's local
telephone operations posted a 4% rise in operating profit to
$720 million on a 5% revenue increase to $3.2 billion. Among
other things, the results reflect higher foreign revenue, a
4% increase in lines in service and an 11% jump in
minute-of-use of local long-distance calling.
   Telecommunications products and services showed a sharp
increase to $37 million from the year-ago $10 million, which
included a provision for a one-time loss on a government
contract. Revenue swelled 37% to $798 million from $580
million.
   Operating profit in electrical-products operations fell
8.2% to $67 million, reflecting stiff competition, lower
foreign results and the impact of the softening automobile
industry. Sales increased 3% to $567 million from $548
million.
   The mobile communication business, which provides cellular
service, attracted 56,000 new customers for a total of
319,000, the company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
