<HL>
   Unicorp American
   Reports Wider Losses
   For Quarter and Year
</HL>
<DATE>
04/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17
</SO>
<CO>
   UAC UNI.A
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Unicorp American Corp., reporting sharply
wider losses of $53 million and $96 million for the 1989
fourth quarter and full year, respectively, said it was
trying to restructure a loan agreement that is already in
default.
   Even if those talks succeed, the troubled real-estate and
financial-services concern said, it can't continue operations
for the next 12 months without an infusion of $15 million in
new funds.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The mounting problems will force Price Waterhouse to
express on Unicorp American's year-end financial statements
"substantial doubt about the company's ability to continue as
a going concern," Unicorp said.
   The per-share loss in the fourth quarter was $3.06. A year
earlier, the company had a net loss of $1.7 million, or 10
cents a share. Revenue rose 3% to $64.9 million from $63
million. The 1988 figures were restated, although it was
unclear why. The number on the company's news release has
been disconnected, according to a phone company recording.
   For all of 1989, the loss per share totaled $5.61. A year
earlier, Unicorp had a net loss of $8.7 million, or 57 cents
a share. Revenue increased 9.4% to $263.1 million from $240.5
million.
   In the negotiations with its bank lenders, which Unicorp
didn't name, the company is seeking a waiver of certain
covenants in the loan agreement, it said. It also is trying
to get an extension of the loan's expiration date beyond
August.
   Assuming that the banks extend the loan agreement, Unicorp
said, "the company believes that it will need at least $15
million in additional funds to continue its operations . . .
for the next 12 months." It said it is talking with the
lenders and its Canadian parent about the additional
financial needs.
</TEXT>
